{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17520633","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17520633"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:26:56+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:26:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13239"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13239","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13239"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.44,0.03,0.12,0.29]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5697"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"40024"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5697","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5697"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13239"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"24756"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1008"},{"type":"tags","id":"1086"},{"type":"tags","id":"1845"},{"type":"tags","id":"1864"},{"type":"tags","id":"2132"},{"type":"tags","id":"2142"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"6610"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9905"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10184"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14401"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43393"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44299"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"40024","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/40024"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 64-year-old man from South Africa is referred to the nephrologist with symptoms of persistent leg swelling and frothy urine. The patient has a history of hypertension, type 2 diabetes, obesity and sickle cell disease. On examination his blood pressure is 141/95 mmHg, pulse 82/min and temperature 37.0\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC. Urinalysis shows +++ for proteins without haematuria. Urinary PCR is 800. Blood glucose and haemoglobin are at normal levels; blood work analysis shows the following abnormalities:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUrea: 14mmol/L (2.5\u20137.8)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECreatinine: 145\u03bcmol/L (59\u2013104)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EeGFR: 63 (\u0026gt;90)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlbumin: 12g/L (35\u201350)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAdditional testing shows the presence of anti-phospholipase A2 receptor antibodies and kidney biopsy is shows a thickened glomerular basement membrane with IgG and C3 deposits in a spike and dome appearance.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"If left untreated, which one of the following complications is this patient most at risk of?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Recurrent infections","Venous thromboembolism","Bladder cancer","Hypertensive encephalopathy","Thrombotic microangiopathy"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EBased on the findings of the patient\u0027s urinalysis, this patient is showing signs of massive proteinuria (above 3.5g/day), without haematuria. Therefore, this patient has a nephrotic syndrome. This patient has \u003Cstrong\u003Emembranous nephropathy. \u003C/strong\u003EMembranous nephropathy is a nephrotic syndrome which predominantly affects older males of Caucasian descent; elevated blood pressure is a risk factor for this condition. The condition is generally classified as either primary or secondary. Secondary causes of membranous nephropathy include infections such as syphilis, malignancy, usage of specific medications such as penicillin and NSAIDS. Primary membranous nephropathy is caused by the presence of anti-phospholipase A2 receptor antibodies, which is present in this patient. A kidney biopsy with \u0022a spike and dome appearance,\u0022 with the presence of a thickened glomerular basement membrane, IgG and deposits of C3 is confirmatory for this condition. Patients with this condition can present with chronic kidney disease, hyperlipidaemia, hyper-coagulability, and signs of AKI, such as low GFR, high creatinine, and low albumin. Treatment for this condition includes the usage of ACEi/ARBs, prednisolone, and cyclophosphamide; monoclonal antibodies may be used in refractory cases.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOf all the listed potential complications, this patient is most at risk of\u003Cstrong\u003E venous thromboembolism, \u003C/strong\u003Eas membranous nephropathy places patients in a hypercoaguable state. If left unaddressed for a long period of time, this can start as a deep vein thrombosis and eventually progress to a pulmonary embolism. Notably, deep vein thrombosis has been shown to occur more commonly in patients with membranous nephropathy compared to other nephrotic conditions. Other major complications of membranous nephropathy are hypertension, hyperlipidemia, and end-stage renal failure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERecurrent infections \u003C/strong\u003Emay occur in membranous nephropathy - however, this tends to be due to the usage of immunotherapy/cyclophosphamide to treat the membranous nephropathy, as opposed to the condition itself. Recurrent infections may also occur in minimal change disease due to loss of IgG, and focal segmental glomerulosclerosis. Similarly, \u003Cstrong\u003Ethrombotic microangiopathy\u003C/strong\u003E may also occur in focal segmental glomerulosclerosis; this is a thrombosis that may occur in the capillaries and/or arterioles as a result of endothelial injury. \u003Cstrong\u003EBladder cancer \u003C/strong\u003Eis not likely to occur due to membranous nephropathy, but instead may occur due to the usage of cyclophosphamide. \u003Cstrong\u003EHypertensive encephalopathy \u003C/strong\u003Eis a hypertensive emergency that also occurs alongside a changed mental status, and is likely to be a consequence of a nephritic syndrome as opposed to a nephrotic syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Membranous nephropathy is a nephrotic syndrome characterised by massive proteinuria, hyperlipidaemia, hyper-coagulability, and signs of AKI.","If left unaddressed, membranous nephropathy can lead to end-stage renal failure, deep vein thrombosis, pulmonary embolism, and hyperlipidaemia","Cyclophosphamide is a treatment for membranous nephropathy, but has potential side-effects such as recurrent infections and bladder cancer."],"references":["Alok A, Yadav A. Membranous Nephropathy. [Updated 2022 Jun 11]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2023 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK559169/","Miao J, Fidler ME, Nasr SH, Larsen CP, Zoghby ZM. Membranous nephropathy in a patient with coronavirus disease 2019 (COVID-19): A case report. Clin Nephrol Case Stud. 2021 Feb 19;9:11-18. doi: 10.5414/CNCS110379. PMID: 33633925; PMCID: PMC7901357.","Smith CC, Conran RM. Educational Case: Membranous Nephropathy. Acad Pathol. 2018 Dec 16;5:2374289518813673. doi: 10.1177/2374289518813673. PMID: 30574541; PMCID: PMC6295683.","Hull, R. P., \u0026 Goldsmith, D. J. (2008). Nephrotic syndrome in adults. Bmj, 336(7654), 1185-1189.","Kazi AM, Hashmi MF. Glomerulonephritis. [Updated 2023 Jun 26]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2023 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK560644/","Guruswamy Sangameswaran KD, Hashmi MF, Baradhi KM. Focal Segmental Glomerulosclerosis. [Updated 2023 Feb 19]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2023 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK532272/","Zamora G, Pearson-Shaver AL. Minimal Change Disease. [Updated 2023 Jul 10]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2023 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK560639/","Sharifian M. Hypertensive encephalopathy. Iran J Child Neurol. 2012 Summer;6(3):1-7. PMID: 24665265; PMCID: PMC3943026.","Lionaki S, Derebail VK, Hogan SL, Barbour S, Lee T, Hladunewich M, Greenwald A, Hu Y, Jennette CE, Jennette JC, Falk RJ, Cattran DC, Nachman PH, Reich HN. Venous thromboembolism in patients with membranous nephropathy. Clin J Am Soc Nephrol. 2012 Jan;7(1):43-51. doi: 10.2215/CJN.04250511. Epub 2011 Nov 10. PMID: 22076873; PMCID: PMC3265338."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"24756"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13239"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"24756","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/24756"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2023-10-27T08:53:10+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-19T00:50:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5697"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"40024"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"13","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/13"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude78","name":"Haematology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"15","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/15"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd54","name":"Nephrology","synonyms":["Renal"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:52:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"h